  1. Write a function for the previous ToDo, so that you can feed it any vector you like (as argument).Usea for-loop in the function to do the computation with each element. Use the standard R function length in the specification of the counter.
func1 = function(v)
{
  v2=c()
  for(i in 1:length(v)){
    if(v[i]<5 | v[i]>90){
      v2[i]=(v[i] * 10)
    } else{
      v2[i]=(v[i]* 0.1)
    }
  }
  return(v2)
}
#run function
v1=seq(1,150)
func1(v1)

  1. People often use more for-loops than necessary.The ToDo above can be done more easily and quickly without a for-loop but with regular vector computations.
func2 = function(v){
  v2=ifelse(v<5 | v>90,v*10,v*0.1)
  return(v2)
}
#run =function
v1=seq(1,150)
func2(v1)
